slot.value:
The payload_limit parameter specifies the number of license steps for the payload capacity. The payload capacity comes in steps of 10 kPPS for GSM and in steps of 50 kPPS for WCDMA, starting from entry levels of 10 kPPS (for GSM) and 50 kPPS (for WCDMA) respectively. The entry level is the capacity license that is included by default. The max throughput capacities for the different hardware configurations can not be evenly divided with 10 (GSM) or 50 (WCDMA). Therefore if max payload capacity for a SGSN-MME is needed, it is enough to buy the nearest possible amount of licenses. 
The number of license steps required is the sum of the quotients given when dividing the actual GSM payload traffic by 10 kpps and the actual WCDMA payload traffic by 50 kpps. Each license step can be shared by both GSM and WCDMA but equals to different amounts of payload capacity depending on the traffic: 10 kpps for GSM or 50 kpps for WCDMA. 

For example, two license steps can be used for granting one of the following: 

*A: 20 (2x10) kpps GSM traffic;
*B: 100 (2x50) kpps WCDMA traffic;
*C: 10 (1x10) kpps GSM traffic and 50 (1x50) kpps WCDMA traffic.;

The total amount of GTP packets during a defined interval is measured at each payload DP and is aggregated for the whole SGSN-MME. The aggregated value is compared to the licensed payload capacity limit, defined by the number of license steps. This capacity limit is a soft limit, i.e. the license can be exceeded without traffic impact, but alarms are generated and all extra use of capacity is logged by the SGSN-MME.

When the payload is 85% of the licensed capacity limit, defined by the number of license steps, the admPayloadLicenseReached alarm is raised indicating that the licensed capacity is soon reached. The alarm is cleared when the payload drops below 70% of the licensed capacity.

When the payload is 100% of the licensed capacity limit, defined by the number of license steps, the admPayloadLicenseExceeded alarm is raised indicating that the licensed capacity is reached. The alarm is cleared when the payload drops below 85% of the licensed capacity limit.
